        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "*The crossing number ([[Crossing number (graph theory)]]) of a drawing is the number of pairs of edges that cross each other.  If the graph is planar ([[planar graph]]), then it is often convenient to draw it without any edge intersections; that is, in this case, a graph drawing represents a [[graph embedding]]. However, nonplanar graphs frequently arise in applications, so graph drawing algorithms must generally allow for edge crossings."
